Title: Kisses from Katie: A Story of Relentless Love and Redemption
Author: Katie Davis Majors
My Review: An honest portrayal of the ups and downs of life, not just in another country but in any circumstance. Didn't necessarily like the format (tell a story about life in Uganda, relate it to a Biblical principle, share a journal entry), and the "journal entries" didn't really seem like they were completely raw, what she had really written in the moment. But overall, a great picture of life and of the ways that we are called to share God's love with others.

Title: Gone Girl
Author: Gillian Flynn
My Review:
When I started this book, I almost put it down after the first few chapters. It was boring, to put it plainly, too contrived and clichéd to have any literary substance.
And then, PLOT TWIST! It became a thriller, a book about two psychopaths inexplicably and dangerously conflicted between their feelings of mutual hatred and love. It's one of those books that leaves a heavy feeling somewhere deep within you. It still felt a little contrived, especially the ending, but it was different, I'll give it that. It kept me interested, but only after struggling through the first half.

Title: Tess of the D’Urbervilles
Author: Thomas Hardy
My Review: I thought that the ending was a bit of a cop-out, but overall I really liked this book. I enjoyed Hardy's style of writing and his "contrived coincidences" didn't bother me as much as people said that they would. I think this is a bit overly negative in terms of Hardy's representation of the human experience, but it was also accurate in terms of the time and reflected the social challenges of the time, especially for women. There were so many good quotes and insights about life in the writing. I was constantly underlining snippets of writing. I'd recommend this to someone who enjoys books written in a bit of an older style but with the classic feel and a driving plot.

Title: The Other Boleyn Girl (The Plantagenet and Tudor Novels, #9)
Author: Philippa Gregory
My Review: It wasn't awful. It had its good points, it selling points, one of which was, for me, that it was historical fiction, which I love, and it was about Henry VIII, another one of my favorite time periods in history. I was disappointed, though. Knowing that it's a story told through the eyes of one of Henry's most famous mistresses, I shouldn't have had such high hopes for it. But I did, and I was let down. I mean, I did like a lot of it. But I felt like it just dragged on so much. It went way too in-depth with every tiny thing. There's a fine line between detailed and boring, and Philippa Gregory crossed that line a hundred times through the course of the book. The basic plot was good, and I liked it. It was almost a satire of England at the time, of the corruption of Henry's reign, of the cycle that Anne Boleyn began by ousting Catherine and going from mistress to wife, which basically then became the goal of every woman in the court. It highlighted perfectly the decline of Henry's reign as he became consumed with his desire for a son so much so that it overshadowed every other aspect of his life and reign. But the book itself, while providing a detailed analysis and scathing criticism of the courts of Europe at the time, neglected to develop that in a well-written and thoughtfully crafted way. The writing was almost as shallow as its subject matter, focusing way more on the romance and the sex and the affairs than the actual plot, which went a lot deeper than that, or the characters, whose development was shoddy at best. I think the problem here is the classification. It's labeled as historical fiction, but in reality the only things historical about it are the characters and the basic events. This would be more accurately classified as a crappy romance novel, set among the ranks of other romance novels whose plot is never developed below the surface of the multiple affairs going on. If you cut out about a hundred pages of absolute nothingness that was totally unnecessary to the overall plot, you might have a barely-stomachable novel. A little fact-checking, working in some more historical nuances, improving the character development, and it would be infinitely better. But as it is, my expectations were definitely not lived up to.

Title: Allegiant (Divergent, #3)
Author: Veronica Roth
My Review: five stars for an amazingly-crafted end to the series. the reason I loved the series so much was because, unlike other dystopian/utopian series, the plot didn't just stretch out over three books, it was new and exciting and it actually went somewhere, somewhere you didn't expect it to go. it wasn't predictable and I loved that aspect of it.

Title: Insurgent (Divergent, #2)
Author: Veronica Roth
My Review: I have to be honest and say that I don't remember much of this book, which is truthfully because I felt it was really basic. Typical dystopian plot, with the revolution and all, the developing love story, memories of the past... I mean, don't get me wrong. it wasn't bad in those parts. the writing was still quality, it was still good and real but there was something that it was lacking, something that I felt was missing, that was keeping me from really getting into it. and slowly you started to have these undercurrents- little hints, some foreshadowing, a promise that something big was about to go down, and it made you want to stick with it - and then the ending. BAM. hits you right in the face like a truck, completely turned the plot around, set the stage nicely for the last book. so, it started out slow, but veronica roth really managed to make it all come together, full circle. I did not see myself liking it when I first read it, but she changed my mind completely. well-done.

Title: Mockingjay (The Hunger Games, #3)
Author: Suzanne Collins
My Review: I feel like the series got progressively lower in quality... this book was my least favorite out of the series. I feel like the first book would've been amazing as a stand-alone novel. the rest of the books, especially this one, didn't really go anywhere... just sort of seemed like they were trying to stretch out the plot and it didn't really work. most of this book felt like an obligatory, almost epilogue, just trying to tie up all the loose ends that probably would've been more interesting had they been left alone. I don't know, I feel like Suzanne Collins' moment in the spotlight started and ended with The Hunger Games, and the next two novels were only her trying to make it last as long as possible. Plus, it's easier to make movies out of a series, I guess, if that's what you're getting at, especially for books that were so well-received by the majority. the movies for catching fire and mockingjay part 1 were admittedly better than the books, though, so maybe my dislike is just something about the way that the action played out in the book versus the way it played out on the screen, which, in my opinion, all came together a lot nicer. but, hey, this isn't a review of the movie, it's about the book, and bottom line is the book felt... I don't know, fake, almost. It was nowhere near the quality of the first book. So, IMHO, Suzanne Collins should've left well enough alone with the first book.

Title: Catching Fire (The Hunger Games, #2)
Author: Suzanne Collins
My Review: not as good as the first, but sequels rarely are. it's always like the author is trying to ride the wave of enthusiasm over the first book, which is either a hit or miss. for me, it was good, but it all seemed a little... stilted. maybe that's not the right word, but I can't think of something more adequate. that's as close to the idea as I can get. I don't really know how to describe it. in it's own right, it was still pretty good though, and I did like it.

Title: Divergent (Divergent, #1)
Author: Veronica Roth
My Review: another favorite. definitely must-read. themes are timeless, characters are well-developed (even more later in the series), language is impeccable... really great, all in all, and better than I expected it to be.
